The publication of Book II must on the ground of the references already discussed in Sat. 2. 6 be put after the winter of ΒΕ. 31. If the connection of Caesar with the Parthians in Sat. 2. 1. ¹5 ‘labentis equo . . . volnera Parthi‚' and 2. 5. 62 ‘iuvenis Parthis horrendus,' be held to refer to the interview of Octavianus with Tiridates during his progress through Asia in B.C. 30¹ we must put it some months later. §4 Satires 2 and 7 of Book I.

In fixing the general date of the composition of Book I we have omitted three Satires which contain no reference verba] or construc- tive to the acquaintance with Maecenas. Of these Satire 4 has nothing to separate it in tone or topic from its neighbours. It was written at some time after Sat. 2, and when Horace felt it necessary if he published that Satire to apologise for its spirit. Satires 2 and 7 however have features which distinguish them from the rest of the Book. Satire 7 turns on a ludicrous incident which occurred in the proconsular court of Brutus when he was in Asia in the year before the battle of Philippi, and while Horace was in his suite. It culmi- nates in the jest on the name of Rex, in connection with Brutus‘ political antecedents,—‘qui reges consueris tollere.' The play on names is of just the kind in which Roman taste delighted 3 and it is quite intelligible that having been one of Horace’s first essays in composition, perhaps one which had been shown to Maecenas by Virgil when he ‘told hini what Horace was like‚' the Satire may have been retained, possibly at Maecenas' desire.
